<HL>
   Silk Greenhouse Posts
   A Loss; Staff Is Cut;
   Financial Aide Quits
</HL>
<DATE>
06/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9
</SO>
<CO>
   SGHI WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   TAMPA, Fla. -- Silk Greenhouse Inc. posted a loss for its
first quarter ended April 30 and said it has reduced its work
force by several hundred employees.
   The company also said its chief financial officer and two
outside directors resigned.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The setbacks sent Silk stock tumbling to $2.125 a share,
down $1.125, in national over-the-counter trading.
   The company -- which sells artificial trees, flowers and
plants -- said its loss totaled $5.7 million, or 60 cents a
share. That compares with earnings of $360,000, or four cents
a share, a year earlier. Sales rose 74% to $27.5 million from
$15.8 million.
   The company cited significant increases in all major
categories of expenses.
   To cut costs, the company said several hundred workers had
been released, both through attrition and dismissals. Eighty
employees were idled at corporate headquarters.
   Chairman and President Jere L. Bradwell said salaries of
several top executives, including his own, had been sharply
reduced. The company declined to elaborate on its loss, the
staff cuts or its outlook.
   Silk also said John Stokely, its chief financial officer,
who had joined the company only last month, had resigned for
personal reasons. Moreover, two outside directors resigned,
also for personal reasons.
</TEXT>
