<HL>
   Commodities:
   Corn and Soybean Futures Contract Prices Spurt
   In Wake of Heavy Rains in Midwest at Weekend
   ----
   By Scott Kilman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
PETROLEUM (PET)
COMMODITY MARKETS FOR METALS (MIN)
</IN>
<LP>
   CHICAGO -- Prices of corn and soybean futures contracts
rose in the wake of heavy weekend rains in the Midwest.
   Analysts said the rains prevented farmers from completing
their rain-delayed planting of the soybean crop. The rains
also washed out some fields and further soaked already
waterlogged corn fields.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The rally follows the steep price declines that occurred
late last week, which were brought on by profit-taking. On
Thursday and Friday, the prices of some soybean futures
contracts dropped a total of about 20 cents a bushel.
   In trading at the Chicago Board of Trade yesterday, the
soybean contract for July delivery rose 10 cents a bushel to
settle at $5.96 a bushel.
   The price of the corn contract for July delivery rose 3.5
cents a bushel to settle at $2.865 a bushel.
   Today, traders will study government reports released late
yesterday that showed that planting of the soybean crop is
only 79% complete nationwide. Usually, soybean planting is
88% finished by this time of the year. Corn planting wraps up
around the first of June.
   Robert Lekberg, an analyst at Farmers Grain &amp; Livestock
Corp., Chicago, said the Agriculture Department's reports
generally fell in line with analysts' expectations.
   Sowing of soybeans is lagging particularly in Illinois,
where only 78% of the crop is planted. Normally, the soybean
planting season is finished in that state by this time of the
year.
   Because of planting delays caused by the unusually wet
spring, most crop analysts have already shaved their original
projections for a corn harvest exceeding 8.1 billion bushels.
Estimates now range from 7.4 billion to 7.8 billion bushels.
   Some traders have been expecting to see a sudden shift in
the weather this summer to hot and dry conditions. But there
isn't any sign of it yet. After the close of trading
yesterday, the National Weather Service's six to 10-day
forecast for the Midwest predicted below-normal temperatures
and normal precipitation.
   Prices of wheat futures contracts settled mixed. According
to Victor Lespinasse, a floor broker with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc., Chicago, China is interested in buying 500,000
metric tons of subsidized U.S. wheat for shipment in October.
   Under a program designed to boost U.S. grain exports, the
Agriculture Department compensates exporters that ship U.S.
wheat to certain countries such as China and the Soviet
Union.
   In other commodity markets yesterday:
                                                                                                       

   ENERGY: The price of crude oil for delivery during July
fell below the important psychological level of $16 a barrel,
finishing yesterday at $15.94 as overproduction and hearty
supply continue to plague that market. The price for the OPEC
basket of crudes fell last week to $14.24, far below the $18
level cartel members had pledged to support at recent
meetings. And there doesn't appear to be any signs that
either Kuwait or the United Arab Emirates plans to reduce
production to quotas assigned them. Both have for months
flagrantly pumped far more than their alloted quotas. "Only
Saudi Arabia {of the major producers in the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries} is holding back on their
output," said Nauman Barakat, first vice president, futures,
for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
                                                                                                       

   COPPER: Futures prices rose. The July contract ended with
a gain of 2.10 cents a pound at $1.1390 after trading as high
as $1.1540. Prices were initially strong on unconfirmed
reports that the Ok Tedi mine in Papua New Guinea was
experiencing labor difficulties. One analyst said there
didn't appear to be any published reports but that talk of
the labor problems circulated in London and then in New York.
When the July price rose above $1.1250, fresh buying orders
were triggered, and a quick rally developed to the high of
the day. Also helping prices rise, the analyst said, were
reports that Asarco Inc.'s negotiations with the union
representing its workers had slowed over local issues. The
current contract runs out June 30. The analyst said there was
no known major risk of a strike taking place. Two other major
U.S. mining companies with contracts that also end on June 30
have recently come to agreement, greatly minimizing the
potential for any supply disruptions. Asarco also is expected
to reach agreement soon. A spokesman for Asarco said the
negotiations had been dwelling a little longer than expected
on local issues but said he had no other comment.
                                                                                                       

   ORANGE JUICE: Futures prices again declined. The July
contract was off 3.20 cents a pound to $1.7630, for a two-day
loss of 13.85 cents. Prices traded over a 9.70-cent range, as
low as $1.70 and as high as $1.7970. At the low, the decline
represented a two-day loss of 20.15 cents. An analyst said
the selling continued from Friday, when a report circulated
that Brazilian juice processors would cut their price. The
report was later denied by the processors, but the selling
continued yesterday mostly on a technical basis, the analyst
said. However, he noted, good support developed at the $1.70
level, and the July contract recovered some of its losses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900619-0023
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900619-0023.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Pathe Replaces Part
   Of Financing Package
   In Bid for MGM/UA
</HL>
<DATE>
06/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7
</SO>
<CO>
   PCC MGM TWX
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- Pathe Communications Corp. said it replaced
part of its financing package for its $1.2 billion tender
offer for MGM/UA Communications Co. and is talking with
MGM/UA about another delay in the offer closing.
   Pathe Communication's $20-a-share offer, already delayed
several times, is set to expire Friday. The original offer in
March specified a final deadline of June 23. Pathe wouldn't
say how much of an extension is now under consideration.
MGM/UA officials couldn't be reached for comment.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Last week, Pathe disclosed that it is raising about $368
million for the offer from a mix of European asset sales and
bank loans. SASEA Holding, a Swiss company of which one of
Pathe's co-chairmen is managing director, had been expected
to raise about $52 million from sales of some or all of its
Banca Agricola Milanese stock. The stock sales weren't
completed, Pathe said.
   Pathe said that SASEA has instead raised about $46 million
from the sale of some or all of its stock in Finarte
Respamio, an Italian finance company. Pathe said the balance
of the $52 million will come from sales of marketable
securities of its parent company, Comfinance S.A. Comfinance
and its European affiliates hold 88% of Pathe's stock.
   Pathe also said that talks are continuing with Time Warner
Inc. concerning Time Warner's agreement to provide $650
million toward the transaction in exchange for certain film
distribution rights and a security interest in the United
Artists film library.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900619-0022
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900619-0022.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Stocks Post Fourth-Biggest Loss of Year,
   Tumbling With Exchange-Listed Shares
   ----
   By Anne Newman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Over-the-counter stocks posted their fourth-largest loss
this year as they tumbled with exchange-listed shares.
   The Nasdaq Composite Index fell 6.76, or 1.45%, to 460.79,
compared with a 1.83% drop in the Dow Jones Industrial
Average. That's the largest decline since a 7.39-point drop
Jan. 30. Declining shares more than doubled advancing stocks,
1,424 to 582, as volume slipped to 157.6 million shares from
168.5 million shares Friday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The day's fall in share prices was orderly and marked by a
lack of buyers, rather than a rush of sellers, traders
agreed. "There was no panic selling," said E.E. "Buzzy"
Geduld, president of Herzog, Heine, Geduld Inc., a New York
dealer for other market professionals. Investors sold stocks
across-the-board and when they did buy, "they were very
particular," Mr. Geduld said.
   Professional dealers were active in the market, according
to William A. Rothe, head of OTC trading at Alex. Brown &amp;
Sons. "The dealers are selling to take advantage of the
momentum," Mr. Rothe suggested, adding that other investors
seemed to be cautious about their next moves.
   At least one OTC trader said he found some signs of
encouragement in yesterday's fall. "I think the fact that
more people are bearish is bullish for the market," said
Richard Bruno, director of OTC trading for PaineWebber. Mr.
Bruno added that he doesn't expect the market's decline to be
prolonged.
   Software Toolworks was the day's most active stock,
dropping 4 7/8 to 19 on nearly 3.5 million shares. A negative
article in Barron's flagged a number of concerns about the
high-flying stock.
   The growing Chatsworth, Calif., software company has seen
its stock price triple in the first five months of 1990,
after tripling in 1989 from a low of $2.50 a share, amid the
prospect the company will sell Nintendo-related products.
Barron's cited the maturation and increasing competitiveness
of the Nintendo market; Software Toolwork's lackluster
outlook; insiders' plans to cash out nearly 30% of their
holdings through a secondary offering; the company's history
of growing by acquisition rather than through operating
acumen, and its possible use of aggressive accounting
practices.
   However, Piper, Jaffray &amp; Hopwood analyst Robert F.
Kleiber advised his clients that the article painted an
"unfair picture" of the company and recommended investors buy
the stock on weakness, according to a detailed rebuttal of
the Barron's piece he sent to clients.
   Potential mergers or buy-outs sparked surges in Healthco
International, which jumped 2 1/2 to 18, and Fiserv, which
rose 2 7/8 to 29 3/8.
   After hiring an investment banker last month, Healthco, a
Boston distributor of dental supplies and equipment, said its
board decided to explore all possible alternatives, including
a possible merger or acquisition. Healthco also said there
have been recent expressions of interest in a transaction
involving the company, but didn't elaborate. The company
scheduled a shareholders meeting for Sept. 6.
   Last month, Gemini Partners L.P., which holds a 9.96%
stake in Healthco, said it intended to seek control of the
company by nominating a slate of candidates to replace the
current board.
   Fiserv, a Milwaukee provider of data processing services,
said it has been approached by a company it wouldn't identify
about a possible corporate combination. The two companies had
preliminary discussions, but Fiserv said it couldn't predict
the outcome of the talks.
   American Steel &amp; Wire was among the day's percentage
gainers with a one-point gain to 7 1/4. Friday afternoon, the
Cuyahoga Heights, Ohio, maker of steel rods and wire declared
a special cash dividend of $3.25 a share, payable June 29.
The company also said it closed on $95 million of new credit
facilities.
   On the other hand, a number of issues were pummeled after
companies reported negative earnings news.
   Silk Greenhouse slid 1 1/8, or 34.6%, to a new 52-week low
of 2 1/8 following a series of adverse news. The Tampa, Fla.,
operator of artificial flower stores reported a loss of 60
cents a share for the first quarter ended April 30, down from
net income of four cents a share a year earlier, reflecting
"substantial" increases in expenses. To curb those costs, the
company said it cut "several hundred" employees from its work
force over the past few months.
   Silk Greenhouse also announced that Chief Financial
Officer John Stokely, who joined the company in May, resigned
on June 8 and that two of its outside directors have resigned
since April 30. No replacements were named. Chairman and
President Jere Bradwell said salaries of certain senior
management, including his own, had been "reduced
significantly." Silk Greenhouse had traded as high as 10 1/8
this year and 24 1/4 within the past 52 weeks.
   IFR Systems plunged 3 1/4 to 9 1/2, or 25.4%. The Wichita,
Kan., maker of communications testing equipment predicted a
decline in profitability for the fiscal year ending June 30,
1991. The company said fiscal 1990 earnings should be in line
with estimates. However, next year's profits will be
pressured by changes in the timing of deliveries under its
Sincgars Army contract, higher production costs for initial
deliveries under the contract, and an acceleration in
research and development and related manufacturing expenses.
   J&amp;J Snack Foods tumbled 2 1/8 to 7 7/8, a 21% decline,
after the Pennsauken, N.J., maker of frozen snack foods said
late Friday it expects earnings for the third quarter ending
June 30 will be lower than the 21 cents a share earned a year
earlier, although sales will be higher. J&amp;J said higher costs
and disappointing retail supermarket sales have hurt
earnings.
   First Commerce dropped 2 1/8 to 19 after the New
Orleans-based bank holding company said late Friday it
expects earnings for the second quarter to be 35 cents to 40
cents a share, down from 58 cents a share a year earlier. The
bank also said it expects provisions for loan losses will be
about $12 million for the second quarter, up from $8 million
in the first quarter and $5 million in the year-earlier
period.
   CSP fell 1 to 5 5/8 after the Billerica, Mass., maker of
array processors and related computer software and hardware
processors reported net income for the third quarter ended
May 31 of a penny a share, down from eight cents a share a
year earlier.
   Multibank Financial eased 3/4 to 11 1/4 after the Dedham,
Mass., commercial bank said late Friday that about $30
million of additions to its loan-loss reserves for the second
quarter ending in June will result in a loss of $11 million
for the second quarter and a loss of $8.1 million for the
first six months of 1990. Multibank reported net income of
$7.4 million, or 79 cents a share, in the year-earlier
quarter and of $14.1 million, or $1.51 a share, for the first
six months of 1989.
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   DEB SHOPS Inc. earned 32 cents a share in the second
quarter of 1989. Wednesday's OTC Focus column misstated the
per-share earnings for that period.
   (WSJ June 22, 1990)
</TEXT>
