<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Police vs. Labyrinth
   Of Search and Seizure
</HL>
<DATE>
06/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A21
</SO>
<LP>
   I appreciated the concerns expressed in your May 7
editorial "Crack, Murder and Miranda." As a police officer, I
have experienced firsthand the impact of the exclusionary
rule. Culpable defendants do indeed walk away laughing while
bewildered victims are left wondering why our courts are
known as part of the "justice system." I must disagree,
however, with your conclusion that law-enforcement officers
themselves should be victimized by "lawsuits, fines, pay cuts
and removal from the force" if they violate the labyrinthine
rules surrounding search and seizure.
   The body of law surrounding Fourth and Fifth Amendment
rights is voluminous and constantly evolving. The justices of
the Supreme Court rarely reach unanimity on any issue, and
many of the court's landmark search-and-seizure cases have
been decided by split votes of 5-4 or 6-3. Professional
police officers, however conscientious, find it difficult to
stay abreast of the latest decisions. If the most learned
jurists in our nation cannot agree what the law should be
after months of careful deliberation, can we expect a
policeman on a dark street at midnight to choose the right
course every time? Can we fine, sue or dismiss him if he
turns out to be wrong?
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Police officers are sworn to protect the constitutional
rights of all people, including criminals. The vast majority
of officers would support sanctions against those few who
abuse their authority. They would also support a
simplification of the laws surrounding individual rights, so
that their decisions can be based on clear-cut precedents. If
an officer who errs in good faith is punished as the Journal
has suggested, the nation will quickly find itself without
anyone willing to fight in the front lines of the war on
drugs.
   Thomas C. Bradley
   Jackson Hole, Wyo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900619-0005
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900619-0005.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   First Boston Head
   Of Junk Bonds,
   Others Reassigned
   ----
   By Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B10
</SO>
<CO>
   Z.CSU WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- First Boston Corp. replaced the head of its
junk-bond department and reassigned other executives amid a
deep slump in its bond financing business.
   The big securities firm named managing director William R.
Reid to head its junk-bond operations, succeeding David M.
Malcolm, who was reassigned to head the firm's real estate
group.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Several other First Boston executives were also moved out
of the junk-bond group, which like most of Wall Street's
departments specializing in high-yield, high-risk bonds,
doesn't have much to do these days.
   Wesley Jones, a managing director, will move to the new
products group, according to people familiar with the firm.
Andrew Fisher, a vice president, is going to the
restructuring group. The moves are the latest signs of
turmoil at First Boston, which has been hit hard by the slump
in the $200 billion public junk-bond market.
   The firm hasn't led a junk-bond underwriting so far this
year. By contrast, in 1989's first half, it raised nearly
$1.4 billion through junk issues, generating $45 million in
fees, according to Securities Data Co. For all of 1989, First
Boston ranked No. 6 among junk-bond underwriters, with an 8%
market share. (Industrywide, Wall Street has raised just $1.1
billion from new junk-bond issues so far this year, a 93%
drop from the year-earlier period.)
   First Boston also has stumbled in refinancing some
temporary "bridge" loans it made to help corporate clients
finance takeovers. Earlier this year, the firm sold to CS
Holding more than half of a "hung" $450 million bridge loan
to Ohio Mattress Co. when First Boston couldn't easily sell
junk bonds in the market to refinance the loan.
   First Boston's parent, CS First Boston Inc., is
44.5%-owned by CS Holding, which owns the Swiss banking giant
Credit Suisse. First Boston earned just $11 million last
year.
   The executive shuffling comes amid a slump in First
Boston's overall bond-financing activities. This year through
Friday, the firm slumped to No. 5 from No. 2 in debt
underwriting, raising $12.4 billion through 61 issues for a
9.7% market share, according to Securities Data. Even with a
$1 billion financing deal yesterday, that's still a 16% drop
from the year-earlier level of $15.9 billion raised through
78 issues and a 12% market share.
   Mr. Malcolm, who joined First Boston in 1979 from Kidder,
Peabody &amp; Co., declined through a spokesman to comment on his
new post. "It's premature to talk about anything," the
spokesman said. Mr. Malcolm, who will oversee the firm's
20-member real estate group, began his career at First Boston
by launching the firm's leasing operations. He was named
managing director in 1982 and has headed the junk-bond group
since December 1984.
   Mr. Malcolm, 43 years old, succeeds William Dickey, a
managing director, who will launch a new real estate division
in Los Angeles, the First Boston spokesman said. Mr. Dickey
will report to Mr. Malcolm; Mr. Malcolm will report to
Charles Murphy, co-head of investment banking.
   Mr. Reid, 34, who joined First Boston's junk-bond
department in 1985, was traveling and couldn't be reached for
comment. He joined the firm in 1980 from the Stanford
Graduate School of Business. After serving as an account
officer, he was named a director in 1987 and a managing
director in 1988.
   Messrs. Jones, Fisher and Dickey couldn't be reached.
   The recent moves aren't the only significant personnel
changes at First Boston lately. Earlier this month, the firm
lost David C. Batten, a managing director since 1978 who
played a major role in building First Boston's capital
markets business, to Blackstone Group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900619-0004
</DOCNO>
